snippet.textDisplay:
The irony of the English triumph. Liverpool's victory in 2019. Here are some thoughts and curiosities to a well-deserved victory.

◘While Firmino is praised by the English in Brazil, doubts persist about his position within the Brazilian national team. Not very popular with the audience but supported by coach Tite. Surely, there will be changes in appreciation after his contribution to the Liverpool title. Something different with Allison , the best goalkeeper in the world who also put his contribution to the victory. He has his position secured. No doubt about that.
◘This was the fourth attempt by Liverpool team since the 80's to get that intercontinental title. Twice defeated by Brazilians and once by Argentines.
◘In South America there is much talk about the gap that has been widening in recent years between continents. Perhaps differences in investment and flexibility in hiring foreigners have their effect ... although some European friends of mine like to think differently. The Liverpool team is the seventh in expenses across Europe Leagues a little more than half of the leader Manchester City with 956 million euros. With PSG and Real Madrid in second and third (source: Transfermarkt). On the other side, Flamengo , one of the richest and most popular in Brazil, does not even enter the Top20 of European clubs in his capital investment. And there is no contrast with macroeconomic indexes such i.e. GDP and cost of living. The difference is mainly in having enough wealth within a football team. There is a huge gap there, no doubt.
◘And the vast majority of young South American players dream of Europe and the best ones get that dream by establishing abroad to savor part of that wealth.
Oh well, that's life as our remembered Sinatra sang masterfully . And everything is valid in favor of having a good football and enjoying it as a spectator.
Congratulations Liverpool, my favorite English team in the Premier.



ps_ Excuse my english, very rusty since my years in the States. I´m just a retired brazilian fellow, who happens to ADORE football or futebol (not soccer as those " yankees" call it!) ,-)
Regards

◘While *Firmino* is praised by the English in Brazil, doubts persist about his position within the Brazilian national team. Not very popular with the audience but supported by coach Tite. Surely, there will be changes in appreciation after his contribution to the Liverpool title. Something different with *Allison* , the best goalkeeper in the world who also put his contribution to the victory. He has his position secured. No doubt about that. 
◘This was the fourth attempt by Liverpool team since the 80's to get that intercontinental title. Twice defeated by Brazilians and once by Argentines. 
◘In South America there is much talk about the gap that has been widening in recent years between continents. Perhaps differences in investment and flexibility in hiring foreigners have their effect ... although some European friends of mine like to think differently. The *Liverpool* team is the seventh in expenses across Europe Leagues a little more than half of the leader *Manchester City* with 956 million euros. With *PSG* and *Real Madrid* in second and third (source: Transfermarkt). On the other side, *Flamengo* , one of the richest and most popular in Brazil, does not even enter the Top20 of European clubs in his capital investment. And there is no contrast with macroeconomic indexes such i.e. GDP and cost of living. The difference is mainly in having enough wealth within a football team. There is a huge gap there, no doubt.
◘And the vast majority of young South American players dream of Europe and the best ones get that dream by establishing abroad to savor part of that wealth.
Oh well, that's life as our remembered Sinatra sang masterfully.  And everything is valid in favor of having a good football and enjoying it as a spectator.
Congratulations Liverpool, my favorite English team in the Premier.

snippet.textDisplay:
Weird referee. Gave weird decisions whole night, stopped play weirdly at times and gave fouls and bookings for seemingly innocuous challenge. It wouldn't surprise me if it escalated into a fist fight late into the game yesterday as a result of his decisions. The penalty incident was the worst of the bunch. It was either one of the following decisions
1) Penalty for the challenge by Rafinha and booking (yellow or red)
2) Freekick for the challenge by Rafina and booking (yellow or red)
3) Dive, booking for Mane and sending off. Goalkick
4) Mane slips, goalkick (low chance of it happening as Mane was hugely invested in the idea of the penalty)

He gave nothing but a dropball after the check. Puzzling! Fair play though that the referee went to the monitors to check, perhaps it was down to the VAR team giving the images which did not show the proper contact on the foot ultimately which could also be a sign that VAR could be improved on with more emphasis on providing time and investing into better cameras and technology to improve on it.
snippet.textOriginal:
Weird referee. Gave weird decisions whole night, stopped play weirdly at times and gave fouls and bookings for seemingly innocuous challenge. It wouldn't surprise me if it escalated into a fist fight late into the game yesterday as a result of his decisions. The penalty incident was the worst of the bunch. It was either one of the following decisions
1) Penalty for the challenge by Rafinha and booking (yellow or red)
2) Freekick for the challenge by Rafina and booking (yellow or red)
3) Dive, booking for Mane and sending off. Goalkick
4) Mane slips, goalkick (low chance of it happening as Mane was hugely invested in the idea of the penalty)

He gave nothing but a dropball after the check. Puzzling! Fair play though that the referee went to the monitors to check, perhaps it was down to the VAR team giving the images which did not show the proper contact on the foot ultimately which could also be a sign that VAR could be improved on with more emphasis on providing time and investing into better cameras and technology to improve on it.

snippet.textDisplay: When I saw the replays, I thought it should have been a free kick too. Rafinha intefered with Mané's right foot and Mané was outside the box when it happened. I didn't think the foul was deserving of a yellow card, but I assume to had to do with the very dangerous (goal-scoring-chance-wise) position that Mané was in, with the time in the match possibly factoring in as well. What I don't get is, if yellow was the appropriate colour card to give if the foul happened inside the 18-yard box, why did the ref have to upgrade it to a red if the foul occured outside the box?
